}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 What is theme.json in WordPress?\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 In WordPress, theme.json is a single configuration file placed at the root of a theme. It defines global settings and styles for both the block editor and the front end using a structured JSON format.\
This file brings consistency and predictability to theme development by centralizing what used to be scattered across functions.php, 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 add_theme_support()
\f0\fs32 \cf2  calls, and custom stylesheets.\
Using JSON makes configurations easier for WordPress to parse and for developers and teams to share. It\'92s the same reason {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/resources/acf-block-configuration-via-block-json/"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 we use it to configure ACF Blocks}}.\
It works in both classic and block themes; it\'92s technically optional, but almost every modern theme includes it as a standard practice.\
This file powers the Global Styles interface in the editor, giving users a visual way to customize colors, typography, layout, and spacing without needing to write code.\
Behind the scenes, it serves as the single source of truth for theme design, feeding four layers of style data \'96 core defaults, block defaults, theme values, and user customizations \'96 which WordPress merges at runtime.\
One of its biggest benefits is reducing the need for excessive {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wpengine.com/resources/customize-theme-css/"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 custom CSS}}. Only the necessary styles are generated, in the correct cascade order, helping to avoid conflicts and unnecessary overrides.\
Beyond styles, theme.json is also extensible: you can define templates, template parts, patterns, and block style variations under structured keys.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-theme-json/#understanding-the-structure-of-themejson"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs60 \cf6 \
\
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 Understanding the structure of theme.json\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Here\'92s a breakdown of the main components you\'92ll define in a theme.json file \'96 and what each one controls.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-theme-json/#schema"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs52 \cf6 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf4 Schema\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 $schema
\f0\fs32 \cf2  key is an optional but recommended top-level entry in theme.json. It links to the official WordPress JSON Schema \'96 typically something like 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json"
\f0\fs32 \cf2 \'a0 \'96 or a version-specific path such as /wp/6.5/theme.json.\
Adding this enables advanced features in modern code editors and IDEs, including autocompletion, real-time validation, and inline documentation for available keys and values.\
It has zero effect on how WordPress renders the theme; it exists purely to improve the developer experience. Some schema validators require it to be listed before the version key, so placing it at the top is best practice.\
While WordPress functions fine without it, skipping it means you\'92ll lose helpful editor features that can prevent syntax errors and speed up configuration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-theme-json/#version"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs52 \cf6 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf4 Version\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 version
\f0\fs32 \cf2  key is a required top-level field in theme.json that tells WordPress which version of the spec your theme uses:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"version": 1
\f0\fs32 \cf2  enables the original feature set introduced in WordPress 5.8, allowing basic global styles and settings.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"version": 2
\f0\fs32 \cf2 , the default since WordPress 5.9, adds support for block-specific settings, layout presets, and deeper editor integration.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"version": 3
\f0\fs32 \cf2 , available in WordPress 6.6+ and recent Gutenberg releases, introduces enhanced style inheritance and lets you define custom CSS variables directly within theme.json.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Each version expands what the theme can configure. If WordPress doesn\'92t recognize the version number, it quietly falls back to version 1 behavior. That means no errors, but also no access to newer features. To prevent this, only update the version key when your theme\'92s minimum WordPress requirement matches the version of the spec you\'92re targeting.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-theme-json/#settings"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs52 \cf6 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf4 Settings\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 settings
\f0\fs32 \cf2  object is the core of theme.json, defining what users can customize in the block editor and setting the design system for your theme. This is where you enable or disable editor features and register design tokens like colors, fonts, spacing, and more.\
Settings follow a hierarchy:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Global settings live at the root of the settings object.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Elements (settings > elements > link, button, heading, etc.) let you target HTML elements directly.\
\ls3\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Blocks (settings > blocks > \'93core/paragraph\'94) allow block-specific overrides.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Common setting groups include color, typography, spacing, layout, border, dimensions, appearanceTools, and custom.\
These settings populate the Global Styles UI, giving users predefined options while preventing option overload. You control what can be changed and what stays locked, reducing inconsistencies across a site.\
Here\'92s an example of what you might find in this segment:\
