\fs52 \cf4 Template parts\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 templateParts
\f0\fs32 \cf2  key registers reusable layout sections \'96 like headers, footers, or sidebars \'96 for use in the Site Editor. These parts live in the parts/ directory of your theme and are referenced by name.\
Each entry includes:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"name"
\f0\fs32 \cf2  is the slug matching a file in parts/ (e.g., parts/header.html).\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"title"
\f0\fs32 \cf2  is the label shown in the editor.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f1\fs28 \cf7 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\cf7 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
"area"
\f0\fs32 \cf2  defines the intended usage zone (
\f1\fs28 \cf7 "header"
\f0\fs32 \cf2 , 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 "footer"
\f0\fs32 \cf2 , 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 "sidebar"
\f0\fs32 \cf2 , etc.).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Here\'92s an example:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs28 \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "templateParts"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 :\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0  \cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 [\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
  \cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \{\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
    \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "name"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 :\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0  \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "header"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 ,\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
    \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "title"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 :\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0  \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "Site Header"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 ,\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
    \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "area"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 :\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0  \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "header"\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
  \cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \}\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 ]\cf0 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \shad0 Registering parts this way exposes them in the Site Editor\'92s \'93Replace\'94 panel, making it easier to swap in alternate versions. It also enables translation of part titles and clarifies their purpose for both users and developers.\
These parts can then be referenced in full-page templates using block markup like 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 <!-- wp:template-part \{"slug":"header"\} /-->
\f0\fs32 \cf2 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs52 \cf4 Patterns\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The 
\f1\fs28 \cf7 patterns
\f0\fs32 \cf2  key allows you to bundle {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-reusable-block/"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 pre-designed block patterns}} with your theme by referencing their slugs. These can come from the official WordPress Pattern Directory or be registered by plugins, e.g.:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs28 \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "patterns"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 :\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0  \cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 [\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
  \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "two-column-cta"\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 ,\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
  \cf9 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 "pricing-table-staggered"\cf2 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
\cf10 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 ]\cf0 \shad\shadx0\shady-20\shadr0\shado255 \shadc0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \shad0 This setup ensures those patterns are readily available in the editor, giving users curated starting points for building pages while keeping your {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wpengine.com/builders/block-theme-templates/"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 block theme templates}} neat and flexible.\
When the theme is activated, WordPress fetches the specified patterns so they appear in the Block Inserter under the Patterns tab.\
This is a lightweight way to provide layout ideas or reusable design sections without hardcoding them into templates. You can also combine bundled patterns with synced (formerly reusable) patterns created in the Site Editor, letting users update all instances of a pattern site-wide from one place.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 How to work with theme.json\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 There are two ways to modify theme.json: by editing the file directly or by using the Full Site Editor (FSE) to adjust styles visually.\
For simple changes like updating colors or fonts, the FSE is often safer and faster, especially for non-developers \'96 it reduces the risk of breaking anything with a syntax error.\
For site owners or editors, the FSE is perfect for rebranding, quick visual fixes, or updates to a live site without needing server access.\
Developers, on the other hand, may use the FSE to prototype styles, then export those settings to commit into code.\
Editing the file directly also allows for advanced configuration, like adding new palette values or using keys not exposed in the UI, and ensures the design system stays version-controlled and portable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

